            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this materials estimation calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool combines the strengths of single-purpose calculators
                (concrete, gravel, paint, drywall, lumber) into one flexible
                worksheet. You can:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Estimate volumes and coverage for common materials with
                  presets.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Add any custom line items in the detailed takeoff table.
                </li>
                <li>Apply waste/overrun and contingency separately.</li>
                <li>Get a clean, copy‑ready summary for quotes or budgets.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Key formulas used</h3>

              <h4>1. Concrete slab volume</h4>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Step 1 – Convert dimensions to feet:</strong></p>
                <p>Thickness in feet:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ t_{\text{ft}} = \begin{cases} \dfrac{t_{\text{in}}}{12} &
                  \text{if thickness in inches} \\ \dfrac{t_{\text{cm}}}{30.48}
                  & \text{if thickness in cm} \end{cases} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  Length and width are converted from meters to feet if needed.
                </p>
                <p><strong>Step 2 – Volume:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ V_{\text{ft}^3} = L_{\text{ft}} \times W_{\text{ft}} \times
                  t_{\text{ft}} \]
                </p>
                <p>\[ V_{\text{yd}^3} = \dfrac{V_{\text{ft}^3}}{27} \]</p>
                <p><strong>Step 3 – Waste / overrun:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ V_{\text{yd}^3,\text{adj}} = V_{\text{yd}^3} \times \left(1
                  + \dfrac{w}{100}\right) \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h4>2. Bulk materials (gravel, mulch, topsoil)</h4>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>Depth conversion to feet:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ d_{\text{ft}} = \begin{cases} \dfrac{d_{\text{in}}}{12} &
                  \text{if depth in inches} \\ \dfrac{d_{\text{cm}}}{30.48} &
                  \text{if depth in cm} \end{cases} \]
                </p>
                <p>Area conversion from m² to ft² if needed, then:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ V_{\text{ft}^3} = A_{\text{ft}^2} \times d_{\text{ft}},
                  \quad V_{\text{yd}^3} = \dfrac{V_{\text{ft}^3}}{27} \]
                </p>
                <p>Waste factor is applied the same way as for concrete.</p>
              </div>

              <h4>3. Paint coverage</h4>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>Convert area to ft² if entered in m²:</p>
                <p>\[ A_{\text{ft}^2} = A_{\text{m}^2} \times 10.7639 \]</p>
                <p>Total coverage needed for multiple coats:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ A_{\text{total}} = A_{\text{ft}^2} \times \text{coats} \]
                </p>
                <p>Gallons required (before waste):</p>
                <p>
                  \[ G = \dfrac{A_{\text{total}}}{\text{coverage per gallon}} \]
                </p>
                <p>With waste factor \(w\%\):</p>
                <p>
                  \[ G_{\text{adj}} = G \times \left(1 + \dfrac{w}{100}\right)
                  \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h4>4. Detailed takeoff line items</h4>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>For each line item:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ Q_{\text{adj}} = Q \times \left(1 + \dfrac{w}{100}\right)
                  \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Line total} = Q_{\text{adj}} \times P_{\text{unit}}
                  \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Best practices for accurate material estimates</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use manufacturer data sheets</strong> for coverage,
                  yield, and recommended waste factors.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Round up</strong> to full bags, sheets, or pallets
                  where appropriate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Separate labor and equipment</strong> – this tool
                  focuses on materials only.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Document assumptions</strong> (thickness, coverage,
                  waste) in your quote or project notes.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How much waste should I allow for materials?</h3>
              <p>
                It depends on the material and project complexity. Typical
                ranges:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Concrete: 5–10% for simple slabs, up to 15% for complex forms.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Tile, flooring, siding: 5–15% depending on layout and cuts.
                </li>
                <li>Paint: 5–10% for touch‑ups and surface variation.</li>
                <li>
                  Lumber and drywall: 10–15% if there are many openings or odd
                  angles.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Does this calculator include labor costs?</h3>
              <p>
                No. The tool focuses on material quantities and material cost.
                You can export the summary and add labor, equipment, overhead,
                and profit in your own estimating software or spreadsheet.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use metric units?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. For the quick estimator you can switch between feet/meters
                and inches/centimeters, and the calculator converts everything
                internally. For the detailed takeoff you can type any unit label
                you like (e.g. “m²”, “kg”, “pcs”) because it treats quantity and
                unit price generically.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this accurate enough for ordering concrete?</h3>
              <p>
                The formulas match standard concrete calculators. Accuracy
                depends on how accurate your dimensions and thickness
                assumptions are. Always:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Measure in multiple places if the subgrade isn’t perfectly
                  level.
                </li>
                <li>Round up to the nearest 0.25–0.5 yd³.</li>
                <li>
                  Confirm with your ready‑mix supplier before placing a final
                  order.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>
